DaVinci Bi-modal integration: MISAR-seq (RNA + ATAC)

Overview

This notebook runs a bi-modal integration workflow (RNA + ATAC) for MISAR-seq data using DaVinci. The overall workflow is:

  1. Horizontal integration within each modality
  2. Vertical (cross-modality) integration between RNA and ATAC, followed by clustering, optional spatial refinement, and visualization

Setup

Load DaVinci and set the working directory.

library(DaVinci)
library(ggpubr)

setwd("~/For_Tutorial/MISAR-seq/")

Part I Preprocess RNA across slices

We load each slice from data.dir/<slice>/RNA.RDS. Each RDS is expected to contain: - mat: feature-by-spot raw counts matrix - coor: spot-by-(x,y) coordinate matrix

For a quick demo, the script subsets to two slices (dataset.opts[3:4]). Remove or modify that line to run all sections.

data.dir <- "~/For_Tutorial/MISAR-seq/data/"


dataset.opts <- list.files(data.dir)

# Work on 2 slices (E15 and E18) as a quick demo
dataset.opts <- dataset.opts[3:4]

Y.list <- list()
L.list <- list()
coor.list <- list()

for (ii in seq_along(dataset.opts)) {
  input <- readRDS(paste0(data.dir, dataset.opts[ii], "/RNA.RDS"))
  
  fin <- preprocess(
    input$mat,
    input$coor,
    type = "rna",
    graph.opt = "Tri.mesh",
    frac.thr = 0.95
  )
  
  Y.list[[ii]] <- fin$mat
  L.list[[ii]] <- fin$L
  coor.list[[ii]] <- fin$coor
}

names(coor.list) <- dataset.opts

Run RNA horizontal integration

Horizontal.Integration.Assemble() searches over a candidate list of latent dimensions (k.arg.list) and integrates robust latent variables across sections.

RNA.res <- Horizontal.Integration.Assemble(
              dataset.opts = dataset.opts,
              Y.list  = Y.list,
              L.list  = L.list,
              coor.list = coor.list,
              k.arg.list = c(4, 6, 8, 10, 11, 12, 13, 15, 16, 18, 20, 22, 24)
            )

Part II Preprocess ATAC across slices

We repeat the preprocessing for ATAC from data.dir/<slice>/ATAC.RDS. In the original script, type is commented out in preprocess() for ATAC. If preprocess() requires a type, set it explicitly (e.g., type="rna" to match other scripts, or type="atac" for ATAC-specific pipelines).

Y.list <- list()
L.list <- list()
coor.list <- list()

for (ii in seq_along(dataset.opts)) {
  input <- readRDS(paste0(data.dir, dataset.opts[ii], "/ATAC.RDS"))
  
  fin <- preprocess(
            input$mat,
            input$coor,
            graph.opt = "Tri.mesh",
            frac.thr = 0.95
  )
  
  Y.list[[ii]] <- fin$mat
  L.list[[ii]] <- fin$L
  coor.list[[ii]] <- fin$coor
}

names(coor.list) <- dataset.opts

ATAC horizontal integration

ATAC.res <- Horizontal.Integration.Assemble(
              dataset.opts = dataset.opts,
              Y.list  = Y.list,
              L.list  = L.list,
              coor.list = coor.list,
              k.arg.list = c(4, 6, 8, 10, 11, 12, 13, 15, 16, 18, 20, 22, 24)
        )

Part III Cross-modality integration, clustering, refinement, visualization

Align shared pixels between modalities

We intersect the row identifiers of RNA and ATAC integrated matrices so that both modalities contain the same set of pixels.

mat.RNA <- RNA.res$mat
mat.ATAC <- ATAC.res$mat

# Intersect pixels present in both modalities
sids.intersect <- intersect(rownames(mat.RNA), rownames(mat.ATAC))
mat.RNA <- mat.RNA[sids.intersect, ]
mat.ATAC <- mat.ATAC[sids.intersect, ]

sids <- rownames(mat.RNA)
mat.slice.id <- unlist(lapply(strsplit(sids, "_"), function(x){x[1]}))

Bi-modal integration and clustering

BiModalIntegration() constructs a shared neighbor graph across RNA and ATAC representations. We then cluster the integrated SNN graph using leiden_adaptive().

integration.res <- BiModalIntegration(
                      modal.1 = mat.RNA,
                      modal.2 = mat.ATAC,
                      n_neighbors = 50,
                      n_neighbors_large = 50,
                      L2norm = "column"
)
## [1] "No adjustment with reference UMI."
partition <- leiden_adaptive(
                      integration.res$snn.mat,
                      num.of.cluster = 15,
                      resolution.start = 0.4,
                      adaptive.size = 2,
                      method = "louvain"
)
## 1.6 0.8 1.6
## 1.2 0.8 1.6
## 1.4 1.2 1.6
## 1.3 1.2 1.4
## 1.35 1.3 1.4
## 1.375 1.35 1.4
partition <- as.character(partition)
names(partition) <- sids

Spatial refinement (local smoothing)

We refine the cluster labels within each slice using KNN-based local smoothing via DaVinci:::refinement().

partition.smooth <- partition

for (ii in seq_along(dataset.opts)) {
  subpart.index <- which(mat.slice.id == dataset.opts[ii])
  
  p.part <- partition[subpart.index]
  p.part <- DaVinci:::refinement(
                  p.part,
                  as.matrix(coor.list[[ii]])[names(p.part), ],
                  neighbor.option = "KNN",
                  neighbor.arg = 8,
                  tasks = "discrete"
  )
  
  partition.smooth[subpart.index] <- p.part
}

Visualize refined clusters

Finally, we plot clusters for each slice using scatter.DiscretePlot.list() and arrange them side-by-side.

par.to_plot <- partition.smooth

plot.list <- scatter.DiscretePlot.list(
  par.to_plot,
  coor.list,
  mat.slice.id,
  dataset.opts,
  pt.size = 2,
  title.size = 30,
  orientation = "x-y",
  ratio = NULL,
  return.obj = TRUE
)

ggarrange(plotlist = plot.list, nrow = 1)
